<p>
  This is the question we hear most often, and the honest answer is: shorter than you think, and
  that's a good thing. Long vows aren't more meaningful vows. If anything, the opposite is often
  true — the vows people remember tend to be the ones that said exactly enough, and stopped.
</p>

<h2>A reasonable target</h2>
<p>
  Most wedding vows land well somewhere between 300 and 500 words, which speaks aloud in roughly
  two to three minutes at a natural, unhurried pace. That's not a hard rule — some ceremonies call
  for something shorter, others leave more room — but it's a useful starting point if you're
  staring at a blank page wondering how much is "enough."
</p>
<p>
  If you're writing a toast or a longer speech rather than vows exchanged at the altar, the
  comfortable range stretches to three to five minutes, since a speech usually needs a little more
  room to set up a story and land it.
</p>

<h2>Why shorter usually works better</h2>
<p>
  Vows are spoken in front of people, in a moment already full of emotion — for you, and often for
  everyone watching. A long list of promises, however sincere, starts to lose its weight around
  promise number seven. The moments that make people cry are rarely the tenth item on a list. They're
  usually one or two specific, well-chosen details that land because there's space around them.
</p>
<blockquote>
  The best writing doesn't sound like it was written by someone else. It sounds like it was always yours.
</blockquote>
<p>
  A shorter, more specific set of vows is also just easier to deliver. Fewer words means fewer
  chances to lose your place, less to memorize or read from a card, and less time standing in
  front of a room feeling the seconds pass.
</p>

<h2>How to tell if yours are running long</h2>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Read it aloud, with a timer.</strong> Not in your head — actually speak it, at the pace you'd use on the day. Silent reading is almost always faster than speaking.</li>
  <li><strong>Count your promises.</strong> If you've listed more than three or four specific promises, look for ones that are really saying the same thing twice.</li>
  <li><strong>Ask what you'd cut under pressure.</strong> Imagine you had to lose 30% of it. What survives? Often, that's the version you should have started with.</li>
  <li><strong>Notice where your voice would naturally pause.</strong> If you can't find a natural place to breathe for more than a page, it may be trying to do too much.</li>
</ul>

<h2>What to do if you're over</h2>
<p>
  Cutting your own words is hard, especially when every sentence feels true. A useful trick: look
  for places where you've described a feeling <em>and</em> given an example of it. Often you only
  need one — usually the example, since specific details tend to carry more weight than
  general statements about how much you love someone.
</p>
